# Modelica Language Specification > Functions > Function Declaration > Function Return-Statements
https://specification.modelica.org/maint/3.6/functions.html#a1stwnmc8g0ku4ik6mytfo5ax

### Function Return-Statements

The `return`-statement terminates the current function call, see [section 12.4](#function-call "12.4 Function Call ‣ Chapter 12 Functions ‣ Modelica® Language Specification version 3.6").
It can only be used in an algorithm section of a function.
It has the following form:

```
return;
```

[Example:
(Note that this could alternatively use `break`:)

```
function findValue "Returns position of val or 0 if not found"
  input Integer x[:];
  input Integer val;
  output Integer index;
algorithm
  for i in 1:size(x,1) loop
    if x[i] == val then
      index := i;
      return;
    end if;
  end for;
  index := 0;
  return;
end findValue;
```

]

# Modelica Language Specification > Functions > Function Declaration > Inheritance of Functions
https://specification.modelica.org/maint/3.6/functions.html#7ndhvatxqj4pc5mevj0odlmyc

### Inheritance of Functions

It is allowed for a function to inherit and/or modify another function
following the usual rules for inheritance of classes ([chapter 7](inheritance-modification-and-redeclaration.html "Chapter 7 Inheritance, Modification, and Redeclaration ‣ Modelica® Language Specification version 3.6")).

[For example, it is possible to modify and extend a `function` class to add default values for input variables.]

A special case is defining a `function` as a short-class definition with modifiers for inputs inside a model.
These default values, unless overridden in the function call, will then be considered for variability similarly as if they were given in the function call, see [section 3.8.1](operators-and-expressions.html#function-variability "3.8.1 Function Variability ‣ 3.8 Variability of Expressions ‣ Chapter 3 Operators and Expressions ‣ Modelica® Language Specification version 3.6").

[Example:
Demonstrating the variability implications.
Note that functions cannot directly use non-constants in enclosing scopes, so we cannot write `input Real x1 = x;` directly in `foo`.

```
model M
  function foo
    input Real x1;
    input Real x2 = 2;
    output Real y;
  algorithm
    y := x1 + x2;
  end foo;
  Real x = time;
  function f1 = foo(x1 = x);
  constant Real z1 = f1(x1 = 2); // Legal, since 'x1' has a new value.
  constant Real z2 = f1(x2 = 1); // Illegal, since 'x' is seen as an argument.
end M;
```

]

